Commentary: OUT! TAKEN! This time there's no mistake! Jason Holder was asking the right questions and has eventually got his prize. Holder comes over the wicket and bowls much fuller outside off. Tristan Stubbs can't resist himself and lunges hard to drill it through cover but gets nicked on the outer edge. The ball zips in the air and flat towards the left and high of third slip. Kavem Hodge swiftly moves in that direction and shows all his reflexes to take the catch. Stubbs will be doubly disappointed. He came pretty early in the session, weathered the storm and battled hard, but at the stroke of Lunch, falls. He did all the hard work, facing 65 balls for his 26, but all that has gone to dust. South Africa are now 57/4!

Commentary: OUT! LBW! And that's it! Gudakesh Motie wraps up things and gets his first wicket. But, this 63-run stand really made the West Indies work a bit more hard. Gudakesh Motie stays around the pegs and drops it in the corridor of the middle and leg stump line, with a hint of turn into the batter. Nandre Burger goes back and across to work it to the leg side but plays over the line of the ball. It sneaks past the inside edge and wears on his back pad. The umpire raises the finger on the appeal for LBW, and Nandre Burger sends it upstairs. Nothing on UltraEdge and Ball Tracking shows three reds as the ball is crashing into the middle and leg stump on the projection. Of what looked like a below triple-figure score, South Africa have well-managed to put on vital runs on the board with this 10th wicket stand, but it is still well below the 1st inning par score at this venue.
Default_Commentary: 53.6: Gudakesh Motie to Nandre Burger, OUT! lbw b Gudakesh Motie.

Commentary: OUT! TAKEN! RABADA GETS HIS FIRST! If one can read the facial expressions, one can see a sigh of relief on KG's face as he was desperately in search of a scalp. Beating the outside edges by around 20 times, and this time he gets the success. He delivers it full and around the middle and leg. Jomel Warrican flicks it flat and aerially but fails to get it in the gap as the bat twists in his hand. Keshav Maharaj stationed at mid on, runs to his right and grabs it well. Jomel departs for a duck and Kagiso Rabada gets his first wicket after 13 gruelling overs in this match. Wicket number 296 for Kagiso Rabada in his illustrious Test career. West Indies trail by 57 runs.

Commentary: OUT! LBW! As plumb as it could get! Jomel Warrican ​​​​​​gives West Indies the early strike on Day 3! Commentary: A huge appeal in unison for LBW and the umpire says 'No'! Temba Bavuma decides to give it a check and sends it upstairs. Commentary: OUT! CHOPPED ON! Wiaan Mulder does win the battle this time around and Keacy Carty departs after getting a golden reprieve without much counterpunch. Wiaan Mulder hurls it at a gentle pace, outside off and deviating away after pitching on the short of a good length. Keacy Carty first goes on the back foot and adjusts by going forward covering the line to play it through the off side. Hence, the lack of clarity gets the better of him as he gets late to bring his bat down in time for the drive and inside edges into the stumps. West Indies are 62/3 now and they need 201 more runs to win. Wiaan Mulder suffocated the batters for runs and got the ultimate prize.

Commentary: OUT! IN THE AIR AND GONE! The plan comes to fruition for South Africa and the smiles on their faces say it all. West Indies slip further into trouble as the hero of the first inning, Jason Holder departs. With a long on in place, Piedt comes from over the wicket and loops it up, full and turning in, on middle, Jason Holder gets tempted in the flight and plants his front foot ahead for the big shot. He looks to hit this with the turn to the right of long on but does not commit to the shot fully. Ends up spooning it straight into the hands of long on where Wiaan Mulder runs a few steps in off the ropes and does the rest. West Indies have slipped to 104/6 now, with 159 runs still to win.

Commentary: OUT! LBW! An appeal for LBW again, and up goes the finger! Joshua Da Silva, however, reviews it in a flash. Keshav Maharaj drops it nice and full, giving a few more revolutions on this one. Pitches it on the middle and leg corridor and drifts it into the batter. Joshua Da Silva gets two-minded whether to commit on the front foot or go deep inside the crease. He first goes back and across but decides to stride on the front foot eventually. He draws his front foot ahead but is too late to get his bat in the line of the ball and wears it on the pads. UltraEdge shows no bat is involved and Ball Tracking confirms that the ball is clipping the leg-pole on umpire's call. This is the second time when the umpire's call has gone the way of Keshav Maharaj and South Africa. Maharaj is now level with Hugh Tayfield at 170 wickets for most wickets as a spinner for South Africa in Test cricket. West Indies lose their 8th wicket and the Proteas are just 2 wickets away now.

Commentary: OUT! TAKEN! Superman effort from the South African skipper! Temba Bavuma, take a bow! Kagiso Rabada comes from over the wicket and bowls a good-length delivery, on off, and shaping it away. Shamar Joseph weighs on the back foot and gives it a swipe across the line. He aims to clear the mid-wicket region but gets it off the cue end of the bat as he loses his shape, trying to hit it too hard. The ball flies flat and towards the mid on fielder where Temba Bavuma leaps and takes a sensational one-handed catch with his right hand to help Kagiso Rabada snag his 299th Test wicket. Shamar Joseph is absolutely distraught and walks back with his head down in disappointment. And with this, South Africa are just a solitary wicket away from a series win.
Default_Commentary: 61.6: Kagiso Rabada to Shamar Joseph, OUT! c Temba Bavuma b Kagiso Rabada.

Commentary: OUT! TAKEN! IT IS SOUTH AFRICA! THEY HAVE CLINCHED THE SERIES WINNING THIS SECOND TEST BY 40 RUNS! Keshav Maharaj bowls fuller and just outside off, and gets a sharp turn towards the middle and leg stump channel. Jayden Seales plants his front foot ahead and looks to turn it with the spin. But ends up chipping it off the inside half of the willow to short leg. David Bedingham in that position quickly reacts to his right, gets his hands in the direction of the ball, and takes the catch in his safe pair of hands. The South African players flock around in jubilation and are all pumped up and why not?
